# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: brunei
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:brunei/15th-punjab-regiment] The **15th Punjab Regiment** was a infantry regiment of the British Indian Army from 1922 to 1947 and of the Pakistan Army from 1947 to 1956.
[src:brunei/15th-punjab-regiment] Following its allotment to Pakistan after the partition of India in 1947, it was amalgamated in 1956 with the 1st Punjab Regiment, the 14th Punjab Regiment, and the 16th Punjab Regiment to form the present-day Punjab Regiment.
[src:brunei/15th-punjab-regiment] The regiment was formed in 1922 by the amalgamation of the 25th, 26th, 27th, 28th, and 29th Punjabis into the British Indian Army.
[src:brunei/15th-punjab-regiment] All five battalions were raised during the upheaval of the Indian Rebellion of 1857 by John Lawrence in Punjab.
[src:brunei/15th-punjab-regiment] The 27th Punjabis served in Qing China during the Second Opium War in 1860–1862, while the 26th and 29th Punjabis participated in the Bhutan War of 1864–1866.
[src:brunei/15th-punjab-regiment] All battalions saw service on the North-West Frontier of British India (now Khyber Pakhtunkhwa, Pakistan) and took part in the Second Anglo-Afghan War of 1878–1880, while the 26th and 27th Punjabis also served in the Third Anglo-Burmese War of 1885–1887.
[src:brunei/15th-punjab-regiment] In 1901, the 27th Punjabis were dispatched to British Somaliland to suppress the resistance movement led by Diiriye Guure of the Dervish State.
[src:brunei/15th-punjab-regiment] During the Second World War, the 15th Punjab Regiment raised / created nine additional active battalions.
[src:brunei/15th-punjab-regiment] Most of the active battalions were engaged in fighting the Japanese in the Far East except the 3rd Battalion, which fought in Somaliland and Italy.
[src:brunei/15th-punjab-regiment] The performance of the 4th Battalion in Burma in particular was outstanding.
[src:brunei/15th-punjab-regiment] The battalion suffered 921 casualties and was awarded numerous gallantry awards including two Victoria Crosses to Lieutenant Karamjeet Singh Judge and Naik Gian Singh.
[src:brunei/15th-punjab-regiment] On the independence of Pakistan in 1947, the 15th Punjab Regiment was allotted to Pakistan Army.
[src:brunei/15th-punjab-regiment] At the time, the active battalions were 1st, 2nd, 3rd and 4th.
[src:brunei/15th-punjab-regiment] Sikhs and Jats were transferred to the Indian Army and the regiment's new class composition was fixed as Punjabis and Pathans.
[src:brunei/15th-punjab-regiment] The 2nd Battalion was reformed as a Medium Machine Gun battalion, moving to Kohat in early 1946; by the time of Partition in August 1947 all the British and non-Muslim officers had left, except for one Indian officer, the Adjutant and he left once all Indian Army personnel moved to India.
[src:brunei/15th-punjab-regiment] The unit helped to escort the 3rd Grenadiers from Kohat to Rawalpindi, after they had been ambushed twice by Pathan tribes.
[src:brunei/15th-punjab-regiment] Other references are the books by Kaushik Roy and Frederick Llewellyn Freemantle (listed below).
[src:brunei/15th-punjab-regiment] The regiment's badge was also modified and the Sikh quoit was replaced by an Islamic star.
[src:brunei/15th-punjab-regiment] In 1948, the 2nd and 3rd Battalions fought in the war with India in Kashmir.
[src:brunei/15th-punjab-regiment] In 1956, a major reorganization was undertaken in the Pakistan Army and larger infantry groups were created by amalgamating the existing infantry regiments.
[src:brunei/15th-punjab-regiment] As a result, the 15th Punjab Regiment was amalgamated with the 1st, 14th and 16th Punjab Regiments to form one large Punjab Regiment.
[src:brunei/15th-punjab-regiment] The four regimental centres were also merged and the combined centre moved to Mardan.
[src:brunei/1962-bruneian-district-council-election] The 1959 constitution had created a 33-seat Legislative Council (LegCo), of which 16 were to be indirectly elected by the district councils, nine were to be appointed by the Sultan and eight were *ex officio*.
[src:brunei/1962-bruneian-district-council-election] As all but one of the district council seats were held by BPP members, it was expected that the party would secure all 16 seats.
[src:brunei/1962-bruneian-district-council-election] However, the government postponed the opening of the Council and later suspended it after the outbreak of the Brunei Revolt in December.
[src:brunei/1962-bruneian-district-council-election] On 20 June 1962 the government declared that elections would take place on 30 August 1962.
[src:brunei/1962-bruneian-district-council-election] There were 55 district council members up for election: 24 for the district council of Brunei (present day Brunei-Muara), 12 for the district council of Belait, 12 for the district council of Tutong, and seven for the district council of Temburong.
[src:brunei/1962-bruneian-district-council-election] A December 1961 Legislative Council (LegCo) law allowed all citizens older than twenty-one to vote.
[src:brunei/1962-bruneian-district-council-election] For each District Council, the elected council members would create an electoral college to choose delegates to the LegCo; eight from Brunei, four from Belait, three from Tutong and one from Temburong.
[src:brunei/1962-bruneian-district-council-election] The date of this election was set for 17 September 1962.
[src:brunei/1962-bruneian-district-council-election] To win as many seats as possible, the *Parti Rakyat Brunei* (PRB) fielded candidates for each of the District Council's fifty-five seats.
[src:brunei/1962-bruneian-district-council-election] There were eight candidates from the Brunei National Organisation (BNO), Hasbollah Daud himself from the Brunei United Party (BUP) and seventeen independents.
[src:brunei/1962-bruneian-district-council-election] This meant the PRB already held control of three of the four district councils, with only Tutong still undecided as all eight seats were contested.
[src:brunei/1962-bruneian-district-council-election] Azahari vigorously advocated for his party.
[src:brunei/1962-bruneian-district-council-election] On 30 August 1962 the results were announced, and the PRB had won all but one of the remaining seats, with Metusin Ali Akbar elected in the Labu constituency in Temburong.
[src:brunei/1962-bruneian-district-council-election] However, Akbar subsequently joined the PRB meaning it held all seats on every council and was guaranteed 16 elected members in the LegCo.
[src:brunei/1962-bruneian-district-council-election] The government was embarrassed as it was an outright rejection of its strategy to include Brunei in the projected Federation of Malaysia.
[src:brunei/1962-bruneian-district-council-election] The overwhelming victory meant that the government was unable to continue to disregard the PRB.
[src:brunei/1962-bruneian-district-council-election] On his birthday, 23 September 1962, Sultan Omar Ali Saifuddien III announced the selection of members of the Executive Council and LegCo, defying persistent appeals from the PRB for a democratic administration and a change to the constitution.
[src:brunei/1962-bruneian-district-council-election] Pengiran Ali, the Head of the Department of Religious Affairs, was appointed to the newly created position of Deputy Menteri Besar, which was established by the Sultan after Dato Marsal's confirmation as the Menteri Besar.
[src:brunei/1962-bruneian-district-council-election] One of the Sultan's closest advisors, Pengiran Ali, was appointed to the new position; this may have been done to bolster his government's position in anticipation of the PRB members' admission to the two councils.
[src:brunei/1962-bruneian-district-council-election] Out of the thirty-three members of the LegCo, the PRB held all sixteen unofficial seats.
[src:brunei/1962-bruneian-district-council-election] The party also held all six of the fifteen-member Executive Council's unofficial (elected) seats.
[src:brunei/1962-bruneian-district-council-election] However, the party was not satisfied since it was still in the minority in both councils even though it had all of the elected seats in both.
[src:brunei/1962-bruneian-district-council-election] The Sultan retained absolute authority to select every member of the Executive Council, in contrast to the LegCo, where the PRB selected its own delegates from each of the four districts through an electoral college.
[src:brunei/1962-bruneian-district-council-election] Consequently, none of the party's Central Executive Committee members were appointed to the Executive Council apart for Abdul Hapidz, the Deputy President of PRB.
[src:brunei/1962-bruneian-district-council-election] Initially, the PRB declined to acknowledge the Sultan's nominations, insisting on having a vote in the appointment process.
[src:brunei/1962-bruneian-district-council-election] Azahari, who abstained from the elections, was not appointed and the elected members of his party were not invited to become part of the government of Brunei.
[src:brunei/1962-bruneian-district-council-election] The sultan chaired a meeting of the committee he had formed to look into the terms and circumstances of Brunei's admission into the proposed Malaysia Federation on the day the nominees were made public.
[src:brunei/1962-bruneian-district-council-election] Twenty-five people made up the committee, which was established in July 1962.
[src:brunei/1962-bruneian-district-council-election] They included the principal local officers and traditional advisers, Dennis White, Joseph S.
[src:brunei/1962-bruneian-district-council-election] Gould, Dato Neil Lawson, and a Chinese community representative.
[src:brunei/1962-bruneian-district-council-election] One of the most important times in Brunei's political and constitutional growth was from September to December 1962.
[src:brunei/1962-bruneian-district-council-election] Serious ramifications resulted from the dominant PRB wanting a larger say in political decision-making, leading to the Brunei revolt.
[src:brunei/1962-bruneian-district-council-election] In addition, Brunei faced pressure to make a decision on its membership in the Malaysia Federation.
[src:brunei/1962-bruneian-district-council-election] Because of how it shaped the new nation, the era was a benchmark in Brunei's modern history.
[src:brunei/1999-southeast-asian-games] The **1999 SEA Games** (Malay: *Sukan SEA 1999*), officially known as the **20th SEA Games** and commonly known as **Brunei Darussalam 1999**, were a Southeast Asian multi-sport event held in Bandar Seri Begawan, Brunei.
[src:brunei/1999-southeast-asian-games] This was the first time Brunei hosted the Southeast Asian Games and also in Borneo island.
[src:brunei/1999-southeast-asian-games] These were the last to have ever staged during the 20th century, and this was the only occasion, to date, that Brunei had held the SEA Games.
[src:brunei/1999-southeast-asian-games] Around 2,365 athletes from 10 participating nations participated at the Brunei Games, which featured 233 events in 21 sports.
[src:brunei/1999-southeast-asian-games] Brunei is the seventh country to host the Southeast Asian Games after Thailand, Myanmar, Malaysia, Singapore, Indonesia and the Philippines.
[src:brunei/1999-southeast-asian-games] The games was held from 7 to 15 August 1999, although several events had commenced from 30 July 1999.
[src:brunei/1999-southeast-asian-games] The games were opened by Sultan Haji Hassanal Bolkiah at the National Sports Complex named after him, Hassanal Bolkiah National Stadium.
[src:brunei/1999-southeast-asian-games] The final medal tally was led by Thailand, followed by Malaysia and Indonesia with host Brunei in seventh place.
[src:brunei/1999-southeast-asian-games] Several Games and National Records were broken during the games.
[src:brunei/1999-southeast-asian-games] The 20th SEA Games Organising Committee was formed to oversee the staging of the games.
[src:brunei/1999-southeast-asian-games] The 1999 Southeast Asian Games used a mix of new, existing and temporary venues.
[src:brunei/1999-southeast-asian-games] Some major retrofitting work were done in most venues to host the multi-sport event.
[src:brunei/1999-southeast-asian-games] At the centrepiece of the activities was the Hassanal Bolkiah Sports Complex which was completed in September 1983.
[src:brunei/1999-southeast-asian-games] Incorporating the 28,000-seat national stadium, it hosted most of the events.
[src:brunei/1999-southeast-asian-games] As Brunei have limited sports facilities, only 21 sports were held in the country.
[src:brunei/1999-southeast-asian-games] Instead, a "village in the city" concept saw athletes and officials housed in were housed in service apartment and hotels respectively across Brunei, with the former served as the games village for the athletes.
[src:brunei/1999-southeast-asian-games] Besides being physically near to the Hassanal Bolkiah Sports Complex, it was hoped that it will add vibe to the city and reduce post-games costs in converting a dedicated games village to other uses.
[src:brunei/1999-southeast-asian-games] The **20th Southeast Asian Games** had 22 venues for the games.
[src:brunei/1999-southeast-asian-games] The logo of the 1999 Southeast Asian Games is an image of a torch, the symbol of the Games that represents vitality, sportsmanship and tradition.
[src:brunei/1999-southeast-asian-games] The logo that is coloured in red, yellow and green symbolises the excitement of the games.
[src:brunei/1999-southeast-asian-games] The ten interlinked gold rings, the logo of the Southeast Asian Games Federation represents the participating nations of the Southeast Asian Games, and the Southeast Asian Games itself.
[src:brunei/1999-southeast-asian-games] The gold colour of the logo represents quality, achievement and victory.
[src:brunei/1999-southeast-asian-games] The games' logo is the first logo in Southeast Asian Games history to use the 10-ring chain which last until the 2011 games.
[src:brunei/1999-southeast-asian-games] The mascot of the 1999 Southeast Asian Games is a boy named Awang Budiman.
[src:brunei/1999-southeast-asian-games] His traditional Malay attire bears the colours of the flag of Brunei, which symbolises the traditional cultural identity of the nation.
[src:brunei/1999-southeast-asian-games] "Awang" is a title for Bruneian males, while the name "Budiman" represents the wise and courteous characteristics of Brunei as the host of the games.
[src:brunei/1999-southeast-asian-games] A song album of the games was released during the games which contains songs written by Prince Sufri Bolkiah.
[src:brunei/1999-southeast-asian-games] These include the theme song of the games: "Mencari Kejayaan" (In search for success) which was composed by Prince Haji Sufri Bolkiah and was sung by Ak Mohd Yusri.
[src:brunei/1999-southeast-asian-games] The other songs are "Here We Meet", "Selamat Datang" (Welcome), "Tekad Kemenangan" (Determined to win), "Skuad Negara" (National Squad) and "Till We Meet Again".
[src:brunei/1999-southeast-asian-games] A total of 9 sponsors sponsored the games.
[src:brunei/1999-southeast-asian-games] At 20:30 BST, His Majesty Sultan Haji Hassanal Bolkiah Muizaddin Waddaulah, Sultan and Yang Di-Pertuan of Brunei Darussalam, Her Majesty Raja Isteri Pengiran Anak Hajah Saleha and the members of the royal family arrived at the stadium.
[src:brunei/1999-southeast-asian-games] The armed forces bringing in the National Flag of Brunei and the National Anthem of Brunei was played as the National Flag of Brunei was raised.
[src:brunei/1999-southeast-asian-games] The Sultan then inspected of the guards of honour of the Armed Forces.
[src:brunei/1999-southeast-asian-games] Later, the march past by 50 flag bearers of the SEA Games flags and Mascot started, followed by 100 flag bearers carrying the flags of all participating nations.
[src:brunei/1999-southeast-asian-games] The contingents of each country also paraded into the stadium began with the Cambodia contingent.
[src:brunei/1999-southeast-asian-games] The host Contingent, Brunei led by Crown Prince Pengiran Muda Haji Al-Muhtadee Billah, Prince Abdul Mateen, Princess Azemah Ni'matul Bolkiah and Princess Fadzillah Lubabul Bolkiah, received the warmest welcome when they marched into the stadium.
[src:brunei/1999-southeast-asian-games] After that, the President delivered his welcoming speech and the games was then declared opened by the Sultan.
[src:brunei/1999-southeast-asian-games] Fathan and Ernie then performed the song Selamat Datang.
[src:brunei/1999-southeast-asian-games] Later, the Royal Armed Force personnel then marched into the stadium taking the games flag with them and raised them beside the Brunei National Flag.
[src:brunei/1999-southeast-asian-games] The 20th SEA Games cauldron was then lit by Dayang Umi Kalthum Haji Karim, Brunei's gold medalist in Pencak Silat event at the 17th SEA Games in Singapore.
[src:brunei/1999-southeast-asian-games] The reading of the SEA Games oath was led by the 15th SEA Games Gold Medalist in Shooting event, Lieutenant Colonel Dato Setia Haji Md Samid Haji Abdul Aziz.
[src:brunei/1999-southeast-asian-games] The ceremony concluded with field performance presented by paratroopers, five-thousand students of Brunei and three hundred Brunei Shell Employees.
[src:brunei/1999-southeast-asian-games] The closing ceremony began at 20:00 BST with the arrival of the Crown Prince at the National Stadium alongside the President of the National Olympic Council of Brunei Darussalam and the Chairman of the 20th SEA Games Organising Committee.
[src:brunei/1999-southeast-asian-games] Also presented were other members of the royal family.
[src:brunei/1999-southeast-asian-games] A song presentation entitled "Skuad Negara" composed by the President of the Brunei Darussalam National Olympic Council was performed by a Bruneian choir group.
[src:brunei/1999-southeast-asian-games] Later, the Crown Prince declared the games closed.
[src:brunei/1999-southeast-asian-games] The national anthem of Malaysia was played as the National Flag of Malaysia was raised.
[src:brunei/1999-southeast-asian-games] Later, a Malaysia segment performance, "Gemilang Malaysia" was performed by members of the Sabah Cultural Board and the Sarawak Cultural Village as well as 60 students from the Bandaraya Kuching Secondary School which formed the Malaysian cultural group.
[src:brunei/1999-southeast-asian-games] The ceremony concluded with a stage performance performed by Bruneian artists.
[src:brunei/2017-asean-summits] The **2017 ASEAN Summits** or the **30th and 31st ASEAN Summits** were diplomatic conferences centering on the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) which were held in the Philippines from 28 to 29 April and 10–14 November 2017.
[src:brunei/2017-asean-summits] This marks the third and fourth time the ASEAN Summit was held in the Philippines.
[src:brunei/2017-asean-summits] The Committee for Security, Peace and Order and Emergency Preparedness and Response was organized to ensure security during the ASEAN Summit.
[src:brunei/2017-asean-summits] For the 30th summit, 40,000 soldiers, 240 motorcycles, 120 patrol cars, as well as 45 air and naval assets were deployed.
[src:brunei/2017-asean-summits] They also urged for self-restraint for all parties concern.
[src:brunei/2017-asean-summits] The following day the "ASEAN Declaration on the Role of the Civil Service as a Catalyst for Achieving the ASEAN Community Vision 2025" was signed by the member countries of the ASEAN.
[src:brunei/2017-asean-summits] The ASEAN member states pledged to promote accountability and transparency in civil service in the region and it is agreed that relevant civil service bodies of each member state will cooperate through the ASEAN Cooperation on Civil Service Matters (ACCSM).
[src:brunei/2017-asean-summits] It was expected that concrete measures to be done to implement the declaration will be discussed in the 31st ASEAN Summit which was held in November 2017.
[src:brunei/2017-asean-summits] The culminating event was held in Manila on 10–14 November (31st summit).
[src:brunei/2017-asean-summits] Despite some criticism on ASEAN's handling of the Rohingya crisis in Myanmar, many viewed the Philippines' performance as a success.
[src:brunei/2017-asean-summits] According to political analyst Richard Javad Heydarian, "Overall, Duterte was a clear big winner at the summit, as he eagerly welcomed the courtship of all major powers, including America, China, Japan, Russia and India.
[src:brunei/2017-asean-summits] The Filipino president deftly leveraged the event to effectively legitimize his leadership and present himself as a regional powerbroker...upon the summit’s conclusion, Duterte’s Philippines never looked as confident and secure.
[src:brunei/2017-asean-summits] All heads of government of the member states of the Association of Southeast Asian Nations except Myanmar attended the 30th ASEAN Summit.
[src:brunei/2017-asean-summits] In the case of Myanmar, the country was represented by its State Counsellor, Aung San Suu Kyi.
[src:brunei/2023-arab-islamic-extraordinary-summit] The **2023 Arab–Islamic extraordinary summit** was organized between the Arab League and the Organization of Islamic Cooperation on 11 November 2023, in Riyadh, the capital of Saudi Arabia, chaired by Crown Prince and Prime Minister Mohammed bin Salman.
[src:brunei/2023-arab-islamic-extraordinary-summit] The urgent meeting was prompted by the Gaza war.
[src:brunei/2023-arab-islamic-extraordinary-summit] The summit was widely criticized for its substandard outcomes and for repeating the same speeches and statements as previous summits.
[src:brunei/2023-arab-islamic-extraordinary-summit] Algeria boycotted the meeting because its proposals were not adopted, and sent a low-level delegation.
[src:brunei/2023-arab-islamic-extraordinary-summit] On 7 October 2023, the paramilitary wing of Hamas led a series of attacks on Israel, resulting in significant loss of life.
[src:brunei/2023-arab-islamic-extraordinary-summit] Israel responded to these attacks with heavy strikes on the Gaza Strip.
[src:brunei/2023-arab-islamic-extraordinary-summit] The stated primary goal of this meeting was to tackle the ongoing crisis in Gaza and its neighboring regions, paying specific attention to the worsening conditions that endanger civilian lives and regional stability.
[src:brunei/2023-arab-islamic-extraordinary-summit] The summit condemned "Israeli aggression on the Gaza Strip, war crimes and barbaric and inhumane massacres by the occupation government" and called for ending the blockade of Gaza, allowing humanitarian aid, and halting arms exports to Israel.
[src:brunei/2025-asean-summits] , Anwar Ibrahim, in the 47th ASEAN summit.
[src:brunei/2025-asean-summits] The **2025 ASEAN Summits**, also known as the **46th and 47th ASEAN Summits**, were diplomatic conferences centering on the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) which were held in Malaysia from 26 to 27 May 2025 and 26 to 28 October 2025.
[src:brunei/2025-asean-summits] This marks the fifth and sixth time the ASEAN Summit was held in Malaysia.
[src:brunei/2025-asean-summits] Under Malaysia’s chairmanship in 2025, Malaysia was the host for the ASEAN Summits.
[src:brunei/2025-asean-summits] With talks on the South China Sea, the Regional Comprehensive Economic Partnership (RCEP), and the development of the ASEAN Economic Community (AEC), Malaysia sought to make sure that the summit's agenda represented the various needs and goals of ASEAN member nations.
[src:brunei/2025-asean-summits] By consulting with ASEAN leaders, Malaysian officials — including Prime Minister Anwar Ibrahim — played a crucial part in the summit's preparations and made sure that Malaysia's interests were taken into account within the larger regional framework.
[src:brunei/2025-asean-summits] The culminating event was held in Malaysia on 26–28 October 2025 (47th summit).
[src:brunei/2025-asean-summits] The regional gathering's topic this year was "*Inclusivity and Sustainability*".
[src:brunei/2025-asean-summits] It was anticipated to be the largest ASEAN Summit since its founding in 1976.
[src:brunei/2025-asean-summits] One week before the summit, police officers were positioned along all main roads leading to the convention center as part of the increased security measures.
[src:brunei/2025-asean-summits] To guarantee efficient automobile and delegation circulation, traffic police ran control simulations.
[src:brunei/2025-asean-summits] Major roads were closed intermittently before and during the Summit.
[src:brunei/2025-asean-summits] Malaysia will handover the ASEAN chairmanship to the Philippines for 2026.
[src:brunei/bn] The domain is administered by BNNIC, a unit under the Authority for Info-communications Technology Industry.
[src:brunei/bn] There are currently two registrars: Imagine and Datastream Digital.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] At the Sultanate of Brunei's peak during the reign of Sultan Bolkiah (1485–1528), the state is claimed to have had control over most of Borneo, including modern-day Sarawak and Sabah, as well as the Sulu archipelago and the islands off the northwestern tip of Borneo.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] There are also claims to its historical control over Seludong, which scholars believe is either Mount Selurong, in Indonesia, or Serudong River in eastern Sabah.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The maritime state of Brunei was visited by the surviving crew of the Magellan Expedition in 1521, and in 1578 it fought against Spain in the Castilian War.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] During the 19th century, the Bruneian Empire began to decline.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The Sultanate ceded Kuching to James Brooke and installed him as the White Rajah, and it ceded Sabah to the British North Borneo Chartered Company.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] In 1888, Brunei became a British protectorate and in 1906 was assigned a British resident as colonial manager .
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] After the Japanese occupation during World War II, a new constitution was written in 1959.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] In 1962, a small armed rebellion against the monarchy, which was indirectly related to the Indonesia–Malaysia confrontation, was ended with British assistance and led to the ban of the pro-independence Brunei People's Party.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The revolt also influenced the Sultan's decision not to join the Malaysian Federation while it was being formed.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Britain's protectorate over Brunei ended on 1 January 1984, when Brunei became a fully sovereign state.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Brunei has been led by Sultan Hassanal Bolkiah since 1967.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The country's unicameral legislature, the Legislative Council, is simply consultative and all its members are appointed by the Sultan.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The country's wealth derives from its extensive petroleum and natural gas fields.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Economic growth during the 1990s and 2000s has transformed Brunei into an industrialised country, with its gross domestic product (GDP) increasing 56% between 1999 and 2008.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Political stability is maintained by the House of Bolkiah by providing a welfare state for its citizens, with free or significant subsidies in regards to housing, healthcare and education.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] It ranks "very high" on the Human Development Index (HDI)—the second-highest among Southeast Asian states after Singapore, with which it maintains close relations including a Currency Interchangeability Agreement.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] According to the International Monetary Fund (IMF), Brunei is ranked seventh in the world by gross domestic product per capita at purchasing power parity.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Brunei is a member of the United Nations, the World Trade Organization, the East Asia Summit, the Organisation of Islamic Cooperation, the Non-Aligned Movement, the Commonwealth of Nations, and the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN).
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] According to local historiography, Brunei was founded by Awang Alak Betatar, later to be Sultan Muhammad Shah, reigning around AD 1400.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] He moved from Garang in the Temburong District to the Brunei River estuary, discovering Brunei.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] According to legend, upon landing he exclaimed, *"Baru nah!"* (loosely translated as "that's it!" or "there!"), from which the name "Brunei" was derived.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] He was the first Muslim ruler of Brunei.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Before the rise of the Bruneian Empire under the Muslim Bolkiah dynasty, Brunei is believed to have been under Buddhist rulers.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] It was renamed *Barunai* in the 14th century, possibly influenced by the Sanskrit **varuṇ** (वरुण), meaning "seafarers".
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The word "Borneo" is of the same origin.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] In the country's full name of **Negara Brunei Darussalam**, the word **darussalam** (Arabic: دار السلام) means "Abode of Peace", while **negara** means "country" in Malay.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] A shortened version of the official Malay name, "Brunei Darussalam", has also entered common usage, particularly in official contexts, and is present in the United Nations Group of Experts on Geographical Names geographical database, as well as official ASEAN and Commonwealth listings.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Areas comprising what is now Brunei participated in the Maritime Jade Road, as ascertained by archaeological research.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The trading network existed for 3,000 years, between 2000 BC to 1000 AD.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The settlement known as Vijayapura was a vassal-state to the Buddhist Srivijaya empire and was thought to be located in Borneo's Northwest which flourished in the 7th Century.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Vijayapura itself upon earlier in its history, was a rump state of the fallen multi-ethnic: Austronesian, Austroasiatic and Indian, Funan Civilization; previously located in what is now Cambodia.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] This alternative Srivijaya known as Vijayapura referring to Brunei, was known to Arabic sources as “Sribuza”.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] One of the earliest Chinese records of an independent kingdom in Borneo is the 977 AD letter to the Chinese emperor from the ruler of Boni, which some scholars believe to refer to Borneo.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The Bruneians regained their independence from Srivijaya due to the onset of a Javanese-Sumatran war.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] In 1225, the Chinese official Zhao Rukuo reported that Boni had 100 warships to protect its trade, and that there was great wealth in the kingdom.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Marco Polo suggested in his memoirs that the Great Khan or the ruler of the Mongol Empire, attempted and failed many times in invading “Great Java”, which was the European name for Bruneian controlled Borneo.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] In the 14th century, the Javanese manuscript *Nagarakretagama*, written by Prapanca in 1365, mentioned *Barune* as the constituent state of Hindu Majapahit, which had to make an annual tribute of 40 katis of camphor.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] In 1369, Sulu which was also formerly part of Majapahit, had successfully rebelled and then attacked Boni, and had invaded the Northeast Coast of Borneo and afterwards had looted the capital of its treasure and gold including sacking two sacred pearls.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] A fleet from Majapahit succeeded in driving away the Sulus, but Boni was left weaker after the attack.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] A Chinese report from 1371 described Boni as poor and totally controlled by Majapahit.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] When the Chinese admiral Zheng He visited the Brunei in the early 15th century, he founded a major trading port which included Chinese people who were actively trading with China.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] During the 15th century, Boni had seceded from Majapahit and then converted to Islam.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Thus transforming into the independent Sultanate of Brunei.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Brunei became a Hashemite state when she allowed the Arab Emir of Mecca, Sharif Ali, to become her third sultan.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] As customary for close affiliation and alliances in Southeast Asia, the royal family of Luzon intermarried with the ruling houses of the Sultanate of Brunei.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Intermarriage was a common strategy for Southeast Asian states to extend their influence.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] However, Islamic Brunei's power was not uncontested in Borneo since it had a Hindu rival in a state founded by Indians called Kutai in the south which they overpowered but never destroyed.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Nevertheless, by the 16th century, Islam was firmly rooted in Brunei, and the country had built one of its biggest mosques.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] In 1578, Alonso Beltrán, a Spanish traveller, described it as being five stories tall and built on the water.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Brunei briefly rose to prominence in Southeast Asia when the Portuguese occupied Malacca and thereby forced the wealthy and powerful but displaced Muslim refugees there to relocate to nearby Sultanates such as Brunei.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The Bruneian Sultan then intervened in a territorial conflict between Hindu Tondo and Muslim Manila in the Philippines by appointing the Bruneian descended Rajah Ache of Manila as admiral of the Bruneian navy in a rivalry against Tondo and as the enforcer of Bruneian interests in the Philippines.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] However, European influence gradually brought an end to Brunei's regional power, as Brunei entered a period of decline compounded by internal strife over royal succession.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] In the face of these invasions by European Christian powers, the Ottoman Caliphate aided the beleaguered Southeast Asian Sultanates by making Aceh a protectorate and sending expeditions to reinforce, train and equip the local mujahideen.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Turks were routinely migrating to Brunei as evidenced by the complaints of Manila Oidor Melchor Davalos who in his 1585 report, say that Turks were coming to Sumatra, Borneo and Ternate every year, including defeated veterans from the Battle of Lepanto.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Spain declared war in 1578, planning to attack and capture Kota Batu, Brunei's capital at the time.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] This was based in part on the assistance of two Bruneian noblemen, Pengiran Seri Lela and Pengiran Seri Ratna.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The former had travelled to Manila, then the centre of the Spanish colony.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Manila itself was captured from Brunei, Christianised and made a territory of the Viceroyalty of New Spain which was centered in Mexico City.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Pengiran Seri Lela came to offer Brunei as a tributary to Spain for help to recover the throne usurped by his brother, Saiful Rijal.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The Spanish agreed that if they succeeded in conquering Brunei, Pengiran Seri Lela would be appointed as the sultan, while Pengiran Seri Ratna would be the new Bendahara.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] In March 1578, a fresh Spanish fleet had arrived from Mexico and settled at the Philippines.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] They were led by De Sande, acting as Capitán-General.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] He organised an expedition from Manila for Brunei, consisting of 400 Spaniards and Mexicans, 1,500 Filipino natives, and 300 Borneans.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The campaign was one of many, which also included action in Mindanao and Sulu.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The Muslim side was also equally racially diverse.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] In addition to the native Malay warriors, the Ottomans had repeatedly sent military expeditions to nearby Aceh.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The expeditions were composed mainly of Turks, Egyptians, Swahilis, Somalis, Sindhis, Gujaratis and Malabars.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] These expeditionary forces had also spread to other nearby Sultanates such as Brunei and had taught new fighting tactics and techniques on how to forge cannons.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Eventually, the Spanish captured the capital on 16 April 1578, with the help of Pengiran Seri Lela and Pengiran Seri Ratna.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The Sultan Saiful Rijal and Paduka Seri Begawan Sultan Abdul Kahar were forced to flee to Meragang then to Jerudong.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] In Jerudong, they made plans to chase the conquering army away from Brunei.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Suffering high fatalities due to a cholera or dysentery outbreak, the Spanish decided to abandon Brunei and returned to Manila on 26 June 1578, after 72 days.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Pengiran Seri Lela died in August or September 1578, probably from the same illness suffered by his Spanish allies.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] There was suspicion that the legitimist sultan could have been poisoned by the ruling sultan.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Seri Lela's daughter, a Bruneian princess, "Putri", had left with the Spanish, she abandoned her claim to the crown and then she married a Christian Tagalog, named Agustín de Legazpi de Tondo.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Agustin de Legaspi along with his family and associates were soon implicated in the Conspiracy of the Maharlikas, an attempt by Filipinos to link up with the Brunei Sultanate and Japanese Shogunate to expel the Spaniards from the Philippines.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] However, upon the Spanish suppression of the conspiracy, the Bruneian descended aristocracy of precolonial Manila were exiled to Guerrero, Mexico which consequently later became a center of the Mexican war of independence against Spain.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The local Brunei accounts of the Castilian War differ greatly from the generally accepted view of events.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] What was called the Castilian War was seen as a heroic episode, with the Spaniards being driven out by Bendahara Sakam, purportedly a brother of the ruling sultan, and a thousand native warriors.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Most historians consider this to be a folk-hero account, which probably developed decades or centuries after.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Brunei eventually descended into anarchy.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The country suffered a civil war from 1660 to 1673.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The British have intervened in the affairs of Brunei on several occasions.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Britain attacked Brunei in July 1846 due to internal conflicts over who was the rightful Sultan.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] In the 1880s, the decline of the Bruneian Empire continued.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The sultan granted land (now Sarawak) to James Brooke, who had helped him quell a rebellion, and allowed him to establish the Raj of Sarawak.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Over time, Brooke and his nephews (who succeeded him) leased or annexed more land.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Brunei lost much of its territory to him and his dynasty, known as the White Rajahs.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Sultan Hashim Jalilul Alam Aqamaddin appealed to the British to stop further encroachment by the Brookes.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The Protectorate Agreement was negotiated by Sir Hugh Low and signed into effect on 17 September 1888.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The treaty said that the sultan "could not cede or lease any territory to foreign powers without British consent"; it provided Britain effective control over Brunei's external affairs, making it a British protected state (which continued until 1984).
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] But, when the Raj of Sarawak annexed Brunei's Pandaruan District in 1890, the British did not take any action to stop it.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] They did not regard either Brunei or the Raj of Sarawak as 'foreign' (per the Treaty of Protection).
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] This final annexation by Sarawak left Brunei with its current small land mass and separation into two parts.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The British Foreign Office sent Consul Malcolm Stewart Hannibal McArthur to assess Brunei and make recommendations on future British foreign policy in the region.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] McArthur produced his Report On Brunei in 1904 where he recommended the implementation of the Malayan British Residency system and the continued protection of Brunei.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] British residents were introduced in Brunei under the Supplementary Protectorate Agreement in 1906.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The residents were to advise the sultan on all matters of administration.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Over time, the resident assumed more executive control than the sultan.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Petroleum was discovered in 1929 after several fruitless attempts.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Cochrane, smelled oil near the Seria river in late 1926.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] They informed a geophysicist, who conducted a survey there.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] In 1927, gas seepages were reported in the area.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Seria Well Number One (S-1) was drilled on 12 July 1928.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Oil was struck at 297 metres (974 ft) on 5 April 1929.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Seria Well Number 2 was drilled on 19 August 1929, and, as of 2009, continues to produce oil.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Oil production was increased considerably in the 1930s with the development of more oil fields.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] In 1940, oil production was at more than six million barrels.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The British Malayan Petroleum Company (now Brunei Shell Petroleum Company) was formed on 22 July 1922.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The first offshore well was drilled in 1957.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Oil and natural gas have been the basis of Brunei's development and wealth since the late 20th century.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The Japanese invaded Brunei on 16 December 1941, eight days after their attack on Pearl Harbor on the United States Navy.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] They landed 10,000 troops of the Kawaguchi Detachment from Cam Ranh Bay at Kuala Belait.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] After six days' fighting, they occupied the entire country.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The only Allied troops in the area were the 2nd Battalion of the 15th Punjab Regiment based at Kuching, Sarawak.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Once the Japanese occupied Brunei, they made an agreement with Sultan Ahmad Tajuddin over governing the country.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Inche Ibrahim (known later as Pehin Datu Perdana Menteri Dato Laila Utama Awang Haji Ibrahim), a former Secretary to the British Resident, Ernest Edgar Pengilly, was appointed chief administrative officer under the Japanese Governor.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The Japanese had proposed that Pengilly retain his position under their administration, but he declined.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Both he and other British nationals still in Brunei were interned by the Japanese at Batu Lintang camp in Sarawak.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] While the British officials were under Japanese guard, Ibrahim made a point of personally shaking each one by the hand and wishing him well.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The Sultan retained his throne and was given a pension and honours by the Japanese.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] During the later part of the occupation, he resided at Tantuya, Limbang and had little to do with the Japanese.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Most of the Malay government officers were retained by the Japanese.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Brunei's administration was reorganised into five prefectures, which included British North Borneo.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The Prefectures included Baram, Labuan, Lawas, and Limbang.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Ibrahim hid numerous significant government documents from the Japanese during the occupation.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Pengiran Yusuf (later YAM Pengiran Setia Negara Pengiran Haji Mohd Yusuf), along with other Bruneians, was sent to Japan for training.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Although in the area the day of the atomic bombing of Hiroshima, Yusuf survived.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The British had anticipated a Japanese attack, but lacked the resources to defend the area because of their engagement in the war in Europe.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The troops from the Punjab Regiment filled in the Seria oilfield oilwells with concrete in September 1941 to deny the Japanese their use.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The remaining equipment and installations were destroyed when the Japanese invaded Malaya.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] By the end of the war, 16 wells at Miri and Seria had been restarted, with production reaching about half the pre-war level.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Coal production at Muara was also recommenced, but with little success.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] During the occupation, the Japanese had their language taught in schools, and Government officers were required to learn Japanese.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The local currency was replaced by what was to become known as *duit pisang* (banana money).
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] From 1943 hyper-inflation destroyed the currency's value and, at the end of the war, this currency was worthless.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Allied attacks on shipping eventually caused trade to cease.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Food and medicine fell into short supply, and the population suffered from famine and disease.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The airport runway was constructed by the Japanese during the occupation, and in 1943 Japanese naval units were based in Brunei Bay and Labuan.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The naval base was destroyed by Allied bombing, but the airport runway survived.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The facility was developed as a public airport.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] In 1944 the Allies began a bombing campaign against the occupying Japanese, which destroyed much of the town and Kuala Belait, but missed Kampong Ayer.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] On 10 June 1945, the Australian 9th Division landed at Muara under Operation Oboe Six to recapture Borneo from the Japanese.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] They were supported by American air and naval units.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Brunei town was bombed extensively and recaptured after three days of heavy fighting.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Many buildings were destroyed, including the Mosque.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The Japanese forces in Brunei, Borneo, and Sarawak, under Lieutenant-General Masao Baba, formally surrendered at Labuan on 10 September 1945.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The British Military Administration took over from the Japanese and remained until July 1946.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] After World War II, a new government was formed in Brunei under the British Military Administration (BMA).
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] It consisted mainly of Australian officers and servicemen.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The administration of Brunei was passed to the Civil Administration on 6 July 1945.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The Brunei State Council was also revived that year.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The BMA was tasked to revive the Bruneian economy, which was extensively damaged by the Japanese during their occupation.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] They also had to put out the fires on the wells of Seria, which had been set by the Japanese prior to their defeat.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Before 1941, the Governor of the Straits Settlements, based in Singapore, was responsible for the duties of British High Commissioner for Brunei, Sarawak, and North Borneo (now Sabah).
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The first British High Commissioner for Brunei was the Governor of Sarawak, Sir Charles Ardon Clarke.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The Barisan Pemuda ("Youth Front"; abbreviated as BARIP) was the first political party to be formed in Brunei, on 12 April 1946.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The party intended to "preserve the sovereignty of the Sultan and the country, and to defend the rights of the Malays".
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] BARIP also contributed to the composition of the country's national anthem.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The party was dissolved in 1948 due to inactivity.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] In 1959, a new constitution was written declaring Brunei a self-governing state, while its foreign affairs, security, and defence remained the responsibility of the United Kingdom.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] A small rebellion erupted against the monarchy in 1962, which was suppressed with help of the UK.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Known as the Brunei Revolt, the rebellion contributed to the Sultan's decision to opt out of joining the emerging state now called Malaysia under the umbrella of North Borneo Federation.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Brunei gained its independence from the United Kingdom on 1 January 1984.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The official National Day, which celebrates the country's independence, is held by tradition on 23 February.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] In July 1953, Sultan Omar Ali Saifuddien III formed a seven-member committee named *Tujuh Serangkai*, to determine the citizens' views regarding a written constitution for Brunei.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] In May 1954, the Sultan, Resident and High Commissioner met to discuss the findings of the committee.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] They agreed to authorise the drafting of a constitution.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] In March 1959, Sultan Omar Ali Saifuddien III led a delegation to London to discuss the proposed Constitution.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The British delegation was led by Sir Alan Lennox-Boyd, Secretary of State for the Colonies.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The British Government later accepted the draft constitution.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] On 29 September 1959, the Constitution Agreement was signed in Brunei Town.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The agreement was signed by Sultan Omar Ali Saifuddien III and Sir Robert Scott, the Commissioner-General for Southeast Asia.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] A series of National Development Plans was initiated by the 28th Sultan of Brunei, Omar Ali Saifuddien III.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] A total sum of B$100 million was approved by the Brunei State Council for the plan.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Bevington, from the Colonial Office in Fiji, was appointed to implement it.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] A US$14 million Gas Plant was built under the plan.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] In 1954, survey and exploration work were undertaken by the Brunei Shell Petroleum on both offshore and onshore fields.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The plan also aided the development of public education.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] By 1958, expenditure on education totalled at $4 million.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Communications were improved, as new roads were built and reconstruction at Berakas Airport was completed in 1954.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The second National Development Plan was launched in 1962.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] A major oil and gas field was discovered in 1963.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Developments in the oil and gas sector have continued, and oil production has steadily increased since then.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The plan also promoted the production of meat and eggs for consumption by citizens.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The fishing industry increased its output by 25% throughout the course of the plan.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The deepwater port at Muara was also constructed during this period.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Power requirements were met, and studies were made to provide electricity to rural areas.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Efforts were made to eradicate malaria, an endemic disease in the region, with the help of the World Health Organization.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Malaria cases were reduced from 300 cases in 1953 to only 66 cases in 1959.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The death rate was reduced from 20 per thousand in 1947 to 11.3 per thousand in 1953.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Infectious disease has been prevented by public sanitation and improvement of drainage, and the provision of piped pure water to the population.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] On 14 November 1971, Sultan Hassanal Bolkiah left for London to discuss matters regarding the amendments to the 1959 constitution.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] A new agreement was signed on 23 November 1971 with the British representative being Anthony Royle.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] This agreement also caused Gurkha units to be deployed in Brunei, where they remain up to this day.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] On 7 January 1979, another treaty was signed between Brunei and the United Kingdom.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] It was signed with Lord Goronwy-Roberts being the representative of the UK.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] This agreement granted Brunei to take over international responsibilities as an independent nation.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Britain agreed to assist Brunei in diplomatic matters.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] In May 1983, it was announced by the UK that the date of independence of Brunei would be 1 January 1984.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] On 31 December 1983, a mass gathering was held on main mosques on all four of the districts of the country and at midnight, on 1 January 1984, the Proclamation of Independence was read by Sultan Hassanal Bolkiah.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The sultan subsequently assumed the title "His Majesty", rather than the previous "His Royal Highness".
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Brunei was admitted to the United Nations on 22 September 1984, becoming the organisation's 159th member.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] In October 2013, Sultan Hassanal Bolkiah announced his intention to impose Penal Code from Sharia on the country's Muslims, which make up roughly two-thirds of the country's population.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] This would be implemented in three phases, culminating in 2016, and making Brunei the first and only country in East Asia to introduce Sharia into its penal code, excluding the subnational Indonesian special territory of Aceh.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The move attracted international criticism, the United Nations expressing "deep concern".
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Brunei is a Southeast Asian country consisting of two unconnected parts with a total area of 5,765 square kilometres (2,226 sq mi) on the island of Borneo.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] It has 161 kilometres (100 mi) of coastline next to the South China Sea, and it shares a 381 km (237 mi) border with Malaysia.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] It has 500 square kilometres (193 sq mi) of territorial waters, and a 200-nautical-mile (370 km; 230 mi) exclusive economic zone.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] About 97% of the population lives in the larger western part (Belait, Tutong, and Brunei-Muara), while only about 10,000 people live in the mountainous eastern part (Temburong District).
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The total population of Brunei is approximately 408,000 as of July 2010, of which around 150,000 live in the capital Bandar Seri Begawan.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Other major towns are the port town of Muara, the oil-producing town of Seria and its neighbouring town, Kuala Belait.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] In Belait District, the Panaga area is home to large numbers of European expatriates, due to Royal Dutch Shell and British Army housing, and several recreational facilities are located there.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Most of Brunei is within the Borneo lowland rain forests ecoregion, which covers most of the island.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Areas of mountain rain forests are located inland.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] In Brunei forest cover is around 72% of the total land area, equivalent to 380,000 hectares (ha) of forest in 2020, down from 413,000 hectares (ha) in 1990.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] In 2020, naturally regenerating forest covered 374,740 hectares (ha) and planted forest covered 5,260 hectares (ha).
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Of the naturally regenerating forest 69% was reported to be primary forest (consisting of native tree species with no clearly visible indications of human activity) and around 5% of the forest area was found within protected areas.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] For the year 2015, 100% of the forest area was reported to be under public ownership.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The climate of Brunei is tropical equatorial that is a tropical rainforest climate more subject to the Intertropical Convergence Zone than the trade winds and with no or rare cyclones.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Brunei is exposed to the risks stemming from climate change along with other ASEAN member states.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Brunei's political system is governed by the constitution and the national tradition of the Malay Islamic Monarchy (*Melayu Islam Beraja*; MIB).
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The three components of MIB cover Malay culture, Islamic religion, and the political framework under the monarchy.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] It has a legal system based on English common law, although Islamic law (*sharia*) supersedes this in some cases.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Brunei has a parliament, but there are no elections; instead, the members are appointed by the sultan.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Under Brunei's 1959 constitution, the Sultan, currently Hassanal Bolkiah, is the head of state with full executive authority.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Following the Brunei Revolt of 1962, this authority has included emergency powers, which are renewed every two years, meaning that Brunei has technically been under martial law since then.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Hassanal Bolkiah also serves as the state's prime minister, finance minister and defence minister.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Brunei is divided into four districts (*daerah*), namely Brunei-Muara, Belait, Tutong and Temburong.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Brunei-Muara District is the smallest yet the most populous and home to the country's capital, Bandar Seri Begawan.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Belait is the birthplace and centre of the country's oil and gas industry.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Temburong is an exclave and is separated from the rest of the country by the Brunei Bay and Malaysian state of Sarawak.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Tutong is home to Tasek Merimbun, the country's largest natural lake.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Each district is divided into several mukims.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Altogether, there are 39 mukims in Brunei.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Each mukim encompasses several villages (*kampung* or *kampong*).
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Bandar Seri Begawan and towns in the country (except Muara and Bangar) are administered as Municipal Board areas (*kawasan Lembaga Bandaran*).
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Each municipal area may constitute villages or mukims, partially or as a whole.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Bandar Seri Begawan and a few of the towns also function as the capitals of the districts where they are located.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] A district and its constituent mukims and villages are administered by a District Office (*Jabatan Daerah*).
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Meanwhile, municipal areas are governed by Municipal Departments (*Jabatan Bandaran*).
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Both District Offices and Municipal Departments are government departments under the Ministry of Home Affairs.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Until 1979, Brunei's foreign relations were managed by the UK government.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] After that, they were handled by the Brunei Diplomatic Service.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] After independence in 1984, this Service was upgraded to ministerial level and is now known as the Ministry of Foreign Affairs.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] With its traditional ties with the United Kingdom, Brunei became the 49th member of the Commonwealth immediately on the day of its independence on 1 January 1984.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] As one of its first initiatives toward improved regional relations, Brunei joined ASEAN on 7 January 1984, becoming the sixth member.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] To achieve recognition of its sovereignty and independence, it joined the United Nations as a full member on 21 September of that same year.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] As an Islamic country, Brunei became a full member of the Organisation of the Islamic Conference (now the Organisation of Islamic Cooperation) in January 1984 at the Fourth Islamic Summit held in Morocco.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] After its accession to the Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation forum (APEC) in 1989, Brunei hosted the APEC Economic Leaders' Meeting in November 2000 and the ASEAN Regional Forum (ARF) in July 2002.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Brunei became a founding member of the World Trade Organization (WTO) on 1 January 1995, and is a major player in BIMP-EAGA, which was formed during the Inaugural Ministers' Meeting in Davao, Philippines, on 24 March 1994.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Brunei shares a close relationship with Singapore and the Philippines.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] In April 2009, Brunei and the Philippines signed a Memorandum of Understanding (MOU) that seeks to strengthen the bilateral cooperation of the two countries in the fields of agriculture and farm-related trade and investments.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Brunei is one of many nations to lay claim to some of the disputed Spratly Islands.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The status of Limbang as part of Sarawak has been disputed by Brunei since the area was first annexed in 1890.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The issue was reportedly settled in 2009, with Brunei agreeing to accept the border in exchange for Malaysia giving up claims to oil fields in Bruneian waters.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The Brunei government denies this and says that their claim on Limbang was never dropped.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] It also hosted the ASEAN summit on that same year.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Brunei maintains three infantry battalions stationed around the country.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The Brunei navy has several "Ijtihad"-class patrol boats purchased from a German manufacturer.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The United Kingdom also maintains a base in Seria, the centre of the oil industry in Brunei.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] A Gurkha battalion of 1,500 personnel is stationed there.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] United Kingdom military personnel are stationed there under a defence agreement signed between the two countries.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] A Bell 212 operated by the air force crashed in Kuala Belait on 20 July 2012 with the loss of 12 of the 14 crew on board.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The cause of the accident has yet to be ascertained.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The crash is the worst aviation incident in the history of Brunei.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The Army is currently acquiring new equipment, including UAVs and S-70i Black Hawks.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Brunei's Legislative Council proposed an increase of the defence budget for the 2016–17 fiscal year of about five per cent to 564 million Brunei dollars ($408 million).
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] This amounts to about ten per cent of the state's total national yearly expenditure and represents around 2.5 per cent of GDP.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Brunei has numerous courts in its judicial branch.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The highest court, though subject in civil cases to the appellate jurisdiction of the Judicial Committee of the Privy Council, is the Supreme Court, which consists of the Court of Appeal and High Court.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Both of these have a chief justice and two judges.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The right of non-Muslims to practice their faith is guaranteed by the 1959 Constitution; however, celebrations and prayers must be confined to places of worship and private residences.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Upon adopting the Sharia Penal Code, the Ministry of Religious Affairs banned Christmas decorations in public places, but did not forbid celebration of Christmas in places of worship and private premises.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] On 25 December 2015, 4,000 out of 18,000 estimated local Catholics attended the mass of Christmas Day and Christmas Eve.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Brunei's revised penal code came into force in phases, commencing on 22 April 2014 with offences punishable by fines or imprisonment.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Stoning to death was the specified "method of execution for crimes of a sexual nature".
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Department of State report stated that discrimination against women is a problem in Brunei.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The law prohibits sexual harassment and stipulates that whoever assaults or uses criminal force, intending thereby to outrage or knowing it is likely to outrage the modesty of a person, shall be punished with imprisonment for as much as five years and caning.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The law stipulates imprisonment of up to 30 years, and caning with not fewer than 12 strokes for rape.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The law does not criminalise spousal rape; it explicitly states that sexual intercourse by a man with his wife, as long as she is not under 13 years of age, is not rape.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Protections against sexual assault by a spouse are provided under the amended Islamic Family Law Order 2010 and Married Women Act Order 2010.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The penalty for breaching a protection order is a fine not exceeding BN$2,000 or imprisonment not exceeding six months.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] By law, sexual intercourse with a female under 14 years of age constitutes rape and is punishable by imprisonment for not less than eight years and not more than 30 years and not less than 12 strokes of the cane.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The intent of the law is to protect girls from exploitation through prostitution and "other immoral purposes", including pornography.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Bruneian citizenship is derived through parents' nationality rather than *jus soli*.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Parents with stateless status are required to apply for a special pass for a child born in the country.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Failure to register a child may make it difficult to enroll the child in school.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Brunei is the first country in Asia to have banned shark finning nationwide.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Brunei has retained most of its forests, compared to its neighbours that share the island of Borneo.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] There is a public campaign calling to protect pangolins which are considered a threatened treasure in Brunei.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Male and female homosexuality is illegal in Brunei.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Sexual relations between men are punishable by death or whipping; sex between women is punishable by caning or imprisonment.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] In May 2019, the Brunei government extended its existing moratorium on the death penalty to the Sharia criminal code, which had previously made homosexual acts punishable with death by stoning.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] In 2019, Brunei announced that it would no longer be implementing the second phase of its controversial sharia penal code.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The code, which was first introduced in 2014, included a range of punishments for crimes such as theft, drug offences, and same-sex relationships, including amputation and death by stoning.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The decision to halt the implementation of the second phase of the code came after significant international backlash and pressure from countries and human rights organisations, who criticised the harsh punishments as inhumane and a violation of human rights.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The government of Brunei stated that the decision was made to maintain peace and stability in the country, and to avoid any negative impact on the economy and reputation of the country.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The Sultan of Brunei, Hassanal Bolkiah, also issued a statement saying that the country would continue to "strengthen and improve" its legal system in line with international norms and best practices.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The first phase of the Sharia penal code, which includes fines and imprisonment for offences such as failure to attend Friday prayers and consuming alcohol, remains in place.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Brunei has the second-highest Human Development Index among the Southeast Asian nations, after Singapore.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Crude oil and natural gas production account for about 90% of its GDP.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] About 167,000 barrels (26,600 m3) of oil are produced every day, making Brunei the fourth-largest producer of oil in Southeast Asia.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] It also produces approximately 25.3 million cubic metres (890 million cubic feet) of liquified natural gas per day, making Brunei the ninth-largest gas exporter in the world.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] *Forbes* also ranks Brunei as the fifth-richest nation out of 182, based on its petroleum and natural gas fields.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Brunei was ranked 88th in the Global Innovation Index in 2025.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Substantial income from overseas investment supplements income from domestic production.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Most of these investments are made by the Brunei Investment Agency, an arm of the Ministry of Finance.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The government provides for all medical services, and subsidises rice and housing.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The national air carrier, Royal Brunei Airlines, is trying to develop Brunei as a hub for international travel between Europe, Australia and New Zealand.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Central to this strategy is the position that the airline maintains at London Heathrow Airport.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] It holds a daily slot at the highly capacity-controlled airport, which it serves from Bandar Seri Begawan via Dubai.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The airline also has services to other major Asian destinations including Hong Kong, Bangkok, Singapore and Manila.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Brunei depends heavily on imports such as agricultural products (e.g. rice, food products, livestock, etc.), vehicles and electrical products from other countries.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Brunei imports 60% of its food; of that amount, around 75% come from other ASEAN countries.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Brunei's leaders are concerned that increasing integration in the world economy will undermine internal social cohesion and have therefore pursued an isolationist policy.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] However, it has become a more prominent player by serving as chairman for the 2000 Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC) forum.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Brunei's leaders plan to upgrade the labour force, reduce unemployment, which was at 6.9% in 2014; strengthen the banking and tourism sectors, and, in general, broaden the economic base.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] A long-term development plan aims to diversify growth.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The government of Brunei has also promoted food self-sufficiency, especially in rice.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Brunei renamed its Brunei Darussalam Rice 1 as Laila Rice during the launch of the "Padi Planting Towards Achieving Self-Sufficiency of Rice Production in Brunei Darussalam" ceremony at the Wasan padi fields in April 2009.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] In August 2009, the Royal Family reaped the first few Laila padi stalks, after years of attempts to boost local rice production, a goal first articulated about half a century ago.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] In July 2009 Brunei launched its national halal branding scheme, Brunei Halal, with a goal to export to foreign markets.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] In 2020, Brunei's electricity production was largely based on fossil fuels; renewable energy accounted for less than 1% of produced electricity in the country.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] As of 2019, the country's road network constituted a total length of 3,713.57 kilometres (2,307.51 mi), out of which 86.8% were paved.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The 135-kilometre (84 mi) highway from Muara Town to Kuala Belait is a dual carriageway.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Brunei is accessible by air, sea, and land transport.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Brunei International Airport is the main entry point to the country.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Royal Brunei Airlines is the national carrier.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] There is another airfield, the Anduki Airfield, located in Seria.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The ferry terminal at Muara services regular connections to Labuan (Malaysia).
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Speedboats provide passenger and goods transportation to the Temburong district.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The main highway running across Brunei is the Tutong-Muara Highway.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The country's road network is well developed.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Brunei has one main sea port located at Muara.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The airport in Brunei is currently being extensively upgraded.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Changi Airport International is the consultant working on this modernisation, which planned cost is currently $150 million.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] This project is slated to add 14,000 square metres (150,000 sq ft) of new floorspace and includes a new terminal and arrival hall.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] With the completion of this project, the annual passenger capacity of the airport is expected to double from 1.5 to 3 million.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] With one private car for every 2.09 persons, Brunei has one of the highest car ownership rates in the world.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] This has been attributed to the absence of a comprehensive transport system, low import tax, and low unleaded petrol price of B$0.53 per litre.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] A new 30-kilometre (19 mi) roadway connecting the Muara and Temburong districts of opened to traffic on 17 March 2020.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] One hundred and forty kilometres (87 miles) of this roadway would be crossing the Brunei Bay.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] The Bank of China received permission to open a branch in Brunei in April 2016.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Citibank, which entered in 1972, closed its operations in Brunei in 2014.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] HSBC, which had entered in 1947, closed its operation in Brunei in November 2017.
[src:brunei/brunei-p01] Maybank of Malaysia, RHB Bank of Malaysia, Standard Chartered Bank of United Kingdom, United Overseas Bank of Singapore and Bank of China are currently operating in Brunei.
[src:brunei/brunei-p02] Ethnicities indigenous to Brunei include the Belait, Brunei Bisaya (not to be confused with the Bisaya/Visaya of the nearby Philippines), indigenous Bruneian Malay, Dusun, Kedayan, Lun Bawang, Murut and Tutong.
[src:brunei/brunei-p02] The population of Brunei in 2021 was 445,373, of which 76% live in urban areas.
[src:brunei/brunei-p02] The rate of urbanisation is estimated at 2.13% per year from 2010 to 2015.
[src:brunei/brunei-p02] The average life expectancy is 77.7 years.
[src:brunei/brunei-p02] In 2014, 65.7% of the population were Malay, 10.3% are Chinese, 3.4% are indigenous, with 20.6% smaller groups making up the rest.
[src:brunei/brunei-p02] There is a relatively large expatriate community.
[src:brunei/brunei-p02] Most expats come from non-Muslim countries such as Australia, United Kingdom, South Korea, Japan, the Philippines, Thailand, Cambodia, Vietnam and India.
[src:brunei/brunei-p02] Islam is the official religion of Brunei, specifically that of the Sunni denomination and the Shafi'i school of Islamic jurisprudence.
[src:brunei/brunei-p02] More than 82% of the population, including the majority of Bruneian Malays and Kedayans, identify as Muslim.
[src:brunei/brunei-p02] Other faiths practised are Christianity (6.7%) and Buddhism (6.3%, mainly by the Chinese).
[src:brunei/brunei-p02] Freethinkers, mostly Chinese, form about 2% of the population.
[src:brunei/brunei-p02] Although most of them practise some form of religion with elements of Buddhism, Confucianism, and Taoism, they prefer to present themselves as having practised no religion officially, hence labelled as atheists in official censuses.
[src:brunei/brunei-p02] Followers of indigenous religions are about 2% of the population.
[src:brunei/brunei-p02] The official language of Brunei is Standard Malay, for which both the Latin alphabet (Rumi) and the Arabic alphabet (Jawi) are used.
[src:brunei/brunei-p02] Initially, Malay was written in the Jawi script before it switched to the Latin alphabet around 1941.
[src:brunei/brunei-p02] The principal spoken language is *Melayu Brunei* (Brunei Malay).
[src:brunei/brunei-p02] Brunei Malay is rather divergent from standard Malay and the rest of the Malay dialects, being about 84% cognate with standard Malay, and is mostly mutually intelligible with it.
[src:brunei/brunei-p02] English is widely used as a business and official language and it is spoken by a majority of the population in Brunei.
[src:brunei/brunei-p02] English is used in business as a working language and as the language of instruction from primary to tertiary education.
[src:brunei/brunei-p02] Chinese languages are also widely spoken, and the Chinese minority in Brunei speaks a number of varieties of Chinese.
[src:brunei/brunei-p02] Arabic is the religious language of Muslims and is taught in schools, particularly religious schools, and also in institutes of higher learning.
[src:brunei/brunei-p02] As of 2004, there are six Arabic schools and one religious teachers' college in Brunei.
[src:brunei/brunei-p02] A majority of Brunei's Muslim population has had some form of formal or informal education in the reading, writing and pronunciation of the Arabic language as part of their religious education.
[src:brunei/brunei-p02] Other languages and dialects spoken include Kedayan Malay dialect, Tutong Malay dialect, Murut, and Dusun.
[src:brunei/brunei-p02] The culture of Brunei is predominantly Malay (reflecting its ethnicity), with heavy influences from Islam, but is seen as much more conservative than Indonesia and Malaysia.
[src:brunei/brunei-p02] Influences to Bruneian culture come from the Malay cultures of the Malay Archipelago.
[src:brunei/brunei-p02] Four periods of cultural influence have occurred: animist, Hindu, Islamic, and Western.
[src:brunei/brunei-p02] Islam had a very strong influence, and was adopted as Brunei's ideology and philosophy.
[src:brunei/brunei-p02] As a Sharia country, the sale and public consumption of alcohol is banned.
[src:brunei/brunei-p02] Non-Muslims are allowed to bring in a limited amount of alcohol from their point of embarkation overseas for their own private consumption.
[src:brunei/brunei-p02] Media in Brunei are said to be pro-government; press criticism of the government and monarchy is rare.
[src:brunei/brunei-p02] The country ranks "Not Free" in media by Freedom House.
[src:brunei/brunei-p02] Nonetheless, the press is not overtly hostile toward alternative viewpoints and is not restricted to publishing only articles regarding the government.
[src:brunei/brunei-p02] The government allowed a printing and publishing company, Brunei Press PLC, to form in 1953.
[src:brunei/brunei-p02] The company continues to print the English daily *Borneo Bulletin*.
[src:brunei/brunei-p02] This paper began as a weekly community paper and became a daily in 1990 Apart from The *Borneo Bulletin*, there is also the *Media Permata* and Pelita Brunei, the local Malay newspapers which are circulated daily.
[src:brunei/brunei-p02] *The Brunei Times* is another English independent newspaper published in Brunei since 2006.
[src:brunei/brunei-p02] A private company has made cable television available (Astro-Kristal) as well as one private radio station, Kristal FM.
[src:brunei/brunei-p02] It also has an online campus radio station, *UBD FM*, that streams from its first university, Universiti Brunei Darussalam.
[src:brunei/brunei-p02] The most popular sport in Brunei is association football.
[src:brunei/brunei-p02] The Brunei national football team joined FIFA in 1969, but has not had much success.
[src:brunei/brunei-p02] Brunei's top football league is the Brunei Super League, which is managed by the Football Association of Brunei Darussalam (FABD).
[src:brunei/brunei-p02] The nation has its own martial arts called "Silat Suffian Bela Diri".
[src:brunei/brunei-p02] Brunei debuted at the Olympics in 1996 and has competed at all subsequent Summer Olympics except the 2008 edition.
[src:brunei/brunei-p02] The country has competed in badminton, shooting, swimming, and track-and-field, but has yet to win any medals.
[src:brunei/brunei-p02] The Brunei Darussalam National Olympic Council is the National Olympic Committee for Brunei.
[src:brunei/brunei-p02] Brunei has had slightly more success at the Asian Games, winning four bronze medals.
[src:brunei/brunei-p02] The first major international sporting event to be hosted in Brunei was the 1999 Southeast Asian Games.
[src:brunei/brunei-p02] According to the all-time Southeast Asian Games medal table, Bruneian athletes have won a total of 14 gold, 55 silver and 163 bronze medals at the games.
